00:25:21.680 --> 00:25:27.069
its energy level be represented
here by this line.

00:25:27.069 --> 00:25:34.000
This is the electron bound to
the metal way down here.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:38.178
And what we know now is that it
takes some energy,

00:25:38.178 --> 00:25:42.015
h times nu nought,
to rip that electron apart,

00:25:42.015 --> 00:25:45.426
to pull it off.
And so I am going to draw

00:25:45.426 --> 00:25:50.457
another energy level up here
which is going to represent the

00:25:50.457 --> 00:25:54.038
energy of the electron free from
the metal.

00:25:54.038 --> 00:25:59.069
So, I will call it "electron
free." And the amount of energy

00:25:59.069 --> 00:26:04.271
that we have to put in to get it
out is this threshold energy,

00:26:04.271 --> 00:26:07.884
h times nu nought.
This energy,

00:26:07.884 --> 00:26:11.646
here, is like an ionization
potential, which you are

00:26:11.646 --> 00:26:14.890
familiar with.
The energy required to pull an

00:26:14.890 --> 00:26:18.651
electron off an atom or a
molecule is the ionization

00:26:18.651 --> 00:26:20.938
potential.
Well, this is like an

00:26:20.938 --> 00:26:24.477
ionization potential.
It really is the ionization

00:26:24.477 --> 00:26:28.165
potential, except since it's
coming off of a metal,

00:26:28.165 --> 00:26:32.000
historically we call it
something else.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:37.930
It's called the work function.
And we give it often the symbol

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:41.236
phi.
But phi and h times nu nought,

00:26:41.236 --> 00:26:46.486
they are the same thing,
the energy required to rip the

00:26:46.486 --> 00:26:50.763
electron off.
And so what we

00:26:50.763 --> 00:26:56.402
know is that the packet of
energy that you send in here has

00:26:56.402 --> 00:27:01.711
to be at least this amount.
In other words,

00:27:01.711 --> 00:27:08.098
if you come in with a photon
and the photon has this much

00:27:08.098 --> 00:27:14.600
energy, E sub i = h nought,
you can ripe the electron off,

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:18.479
but you have to have at least
this.

00:27:18.479 --> 00:27:25.209
Now, you can come in with a
photon that has more energy than

00:27:25.209 --> 00:27:30.000
that, E sub i,
from here to here.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.785
But if you do,
then the rest of this energy

00:27:33.785 --> 00:27:39.014
here, the rest of this energy
goes to the kinetic energy of

00:27:39.014 --> 00:27:42.980
the electron.
